<seg id=1> Two South Korean Soldiers Held Prisoner For 45 Years After Korean War Finally Escape North Korea </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (REUTERS WIRE Seoul) South Korea's National Security Planning Agency said two days ago that two South Korean soldiers who had been listed as dead during the Korean War were actually imprisoned for 45 years before finally escaping from North Korea. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The agency's statement said that 67 year-old Kim Bok-ki and 71 year-old Park Dong-il (names have been transliterated) recently went through three countries before returning to South Korea. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The statement said that the two men were taken prisoner in the northwest, near the North Korean border, by Chinese soldiers during the Korean War. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The statement said the two were forced to work as slaves in a North Korean coal mine. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> After the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, the South Korean defense department listed tens of thousands of missing soldiers as killed in action. Kim Bok-ki and Park Dong-il were on that list. </seg>
<seg id=7> The two Koreas finally signed an armistice, though not an official peace treaty. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> South and North Korea are still technically in a state of war. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> What is so surprising is that the two men became relatives during their captivity. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The statement said that Kim Bok-ki's second-eldest son, Kim Young-gu, and Park Dong-il's fourth-eldest daughter, Park Jung-shim, were married in April of 1991. </seg>
<seg id=11> The statement didn't explain further. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> An official from the National Security Planning Agency said that Kim Bok-ki and  Park Dong-il are currently being retained for questioning by the authorities. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> The defense department has said that about twenty thousand soldiers went missing during the Korean War, and believes that there are still some survivors. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> In April of this year, a prisoner of war who had escaped said that he knew of 50 or 60 South Korean soldiers who are still in captivity in North Korea. </seg>
</p>
